\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Related Literature:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Large literature documenting changes in U.S.
 wage distribution.
 Recent surveys include 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "eckstein2004"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HeathcotePV2010"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two previous approaches that study the evolution of U.S.
 wages through the lens of human capital theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HeckmanLochnerT1998"

\end_inset

 - need to say clearly how this is different
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "guvenen2010nber"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One innovation: show that the model accounts for cohort specific age wage
 profiles.
 More comprehensive comparison with data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jeong2012"

\end_inset

 account for changing experience wage profiles based on changing relative
 prices of experience and raw labor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Model
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Environment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I study a general equilibrium overlapping generations model.
 The model abstracts from physical capital.
 Agents can borrow and lend at an exogenous interest rate (as in a small
 open economy).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Demographics:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In each period 
\begin_inset Formula $\birthYear$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\birthYear}$
\end_inset

 households are born.
 Each lives and works for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lifeSpan$
\end_inset

 periods.
 Denote the year in which a person of cohort 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is aged 
\begin_inset Formula $\age$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pYear(\birthYear,\age)=\birthYear+\age-1$
\end_inset

.
 Denote the cohort aged 
\begin_inset Formula $\age$
\end_inset

 in year 
\begin_inset Formula $\pYear$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\birthYear(\age,\pYear)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Endowments:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At birth, agents are endowed with school level 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\left\{ 1,\dots,S\right\} $
\end_inset

 and with 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{1,s}=1$
\end_inset

 units of human capital (a normalization).
 The mass of households with school level 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{s,\bYear}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To match up with data, need agents to start working at ages that depend
 on schooling.
 Denote these by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ageWorkStart_{s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In each period, a person supplies 
\begin_inset Formula $\tEndow_{s,\birthYear,\pYear}$
\end_inset

 market hours.
 They can be used for work or study.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Preferences:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Upon entering the labor market, individuals maximize the discounted present
 value of lifetime earnings.
 Equivalently, individuals maximize the present value of utility derived
 from consumption subject to a lifetime budget constraint with perfect credit
 markets.
 There is no need to specify the utility function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Human capital production:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Human capital is produced on the job.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the job, human capital is produced from human capital and study time
 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{t}$
\end_inset

 according to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h_{t+1}=(1-\delta_{s})h_{t}+\pProduct(s)(h_{t}l_{t})^{\alpha_{s}}\label{eq:OJT}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Each worker's effective labor supply is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\effUnits_{i,s,c,t}=h_{i,s,c,t}(\tEndow_{s,c,t}-l_{i,s,c,t})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Aggregate production function:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Output is produced from human capital augmented labor according to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\aggrOutput_{\pYear}=\neutralProd_{\pYear}\left[G_{\pYear}^{\rho_{CG}}+(\skillWeight_{CG,\pYear}L_{CG,\pYear})^{\rho_{CG}}\right]^{1/\rho_{CG}}\label{eq:AggrProdFct}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G_{\tau}=\left[\sum_{s=HSD}^{CD}(\skillWeight_{s,\pYear}L_{s,\pYear})^{\rho_{HS}}\right]^{1/\rho_{HS}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is a CES aggregator for unskilled labor (with less than a college degree).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Constant skill-biased technical change:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "KatzMurphy1992"

\end_inset

, relative skill weights, 
\begin_inset Formula $\skillWeight_{s,\pYear}/\skillWeight_{HSG,\pYear}$
\end_inset

 are assumed to grow at constant rates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Markets:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
there are competitive markets for goods (the numeraire) and labor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Skill prices equal marginal products: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sPrice\left(s,\pYear\right)=\partial\aggrOutput_{\tau}/\partial L_{s,\tau}\label{eq:SpMp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These are not observed.
 Observed wages are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\wage_{\age,s,\pYear}=h_{\age,s,\bYear}\skillPrice_{s,\pYear}\label{eq:Wage}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $L_{s,\tau}$
\end_inset

 denotes aggregate labor supply in efficiency units 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\effUnits\right)$
\end_inset

 of school group 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 in year 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Household Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The household is born at age 1 with endowment 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In each working period, he divides his time endowment between job-training
 and work.
 He retires at age 
\begin_inset Formula $\lifeSpan$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Work phase:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He maximizes the discounted present value of lifetime earnings
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V(s,\bYear)=\mbox{\max}_{\{l_{t}\}}\sum_{\age=1}^{\lifeSpan}R^{-\age}\earn(l_{\age},h_{\age},\age,s,\bYear)\label{eq:HhValue}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
subject to the law of motion for 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:OJT"

\end_inset

 and the time constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le l\le\tEndow_{\age,s,\bYear}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 denotes the exogenous gross interest rate.
 Period earnings are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\earn\left(l,h,\age,s,\bYear\right)=\sPrice_{s,\tau(c,t)}h(\ell_{t,s,c}-l)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This problem can be solved analytically using a minor extension of the solution
 given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Huggett2006"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A competitive equilibrium consists of an allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ h_{\age,s,\bYear},l_{\age,s,\bYear}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and skill prices 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ w_{s,\pYear}\right\} $
\end_inset

 that satisfy:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Skill prices equal marginal products (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SpMp"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Given skill prices, households optimally choose on-the-job training to solve
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HhValue"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Labor markets clear: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lSupply_{s,\pYear}=\sum_{\age=\ageWorkStart_{s}}^{\lifeSpan}N_{s,\bYear}h_{\age,s,\bYear}\left(\tEndow_{\age,s,\bYear}-l_{\age,s,\bYear}\right)\label{eq:LaborMarket}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where it is understood that the cohort subscript refers to 
\begin_inset Formula $\bYear\left(\age,\pYear\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Data and Calibration
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Calibration"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Data Moments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The data moments used in the calibration are constructed from the March
 CPS files for 
\begin_inset Formula $\dataYearOne-\dataYearLast$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ipums_cps"

\end_inset

.
 The sample contains men born between 
\begin_inset Formula $\bYearFirst$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bYearLast$
\end_inset

.
 For each year, I calculate 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{N}_{\age,s,\pYear}$
\end_inset

: the mass of persons in each (age, school) cell;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\tEndow}_{\age,s,\pYear}$
\end_inset

: mean hours worked in each cell.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\wage}_{\age,s,\pYear}$
\end_inset

: median wage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Details of the CPS data are described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:AppCPS"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The age wage profiles implied by the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\wage}$
\end_inset

 series form the calibration targets (details below).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hours worked are used to set the model time endowments.
 This is done as follows +++
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fit a quartic to all hours data.
 Impose the same profile on all cohorts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Calibration Algorithm
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:CalibratedParams"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following parameters are calibrated jointly:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
human capital technologies: 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{s},\delta_{s},\pProduct_{s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
skill weights: 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{s,\pYear}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The strategy: Compute the equilibrium for each set of parameters.
 Find the parameters that minimize the sum of squared deviations between
 log model wages (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Wage"

\end_inset

) and log median data wages.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Objective is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D=\sum_{\age=\wageAgeRangeOne}^{\wageAgeRangeLast}\sum_{s=1}^{S}\sum_{\bYear=\bYearFirst}^{\bYearLast}\pWeight_{\age,s,\bYear}\left[\ln\wage_{\age,s,\bYear}-\ln\hat{\wage}_{\age,s,\bYear}\right]^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where it is understood that observations for which data do not exist (
\begin_inset Formula $\pYear\left(\age,\bYear\right)<\wageYearOne$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $>\wageYearLast$
\end_inset

) are dropped.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
weighted by the square root of the number of observations in each data cell
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\pWeight\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Skill prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As described, the solution would be computationally costly.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving the household problem requires skill prices, but deriving skill
 prices from the model parameters requires a solution to the household problem.
 Thus, a fixed point problem would have to be solved for each set of parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To reduce the computational cost, the algorithm searches over time paths
 for skill prices instead of skill weights.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since skill prices are a smooth function of time, they can be approximated
 efficiently by a cubic spline with 
\begin_inset Formula $\nSpNodes$
\end_inset

 nodes for each school group.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The algorithm then searches for the parameter values that minimizes 
\begin_inset Formula $D+P$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 penalizes skill price paths that are not consistent with constant skill-biased
 technical change.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Specifically, recover skill weights from aggregate labor supplies and skill
 prices using the aggregate production function 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:AggrProdFct"

\end_inset

.
 Construct the penalty function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P=\sum_{s}\sum_{\pYear}resid_{s,\pYear}^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $resid_{s,\pYear}$
\end_inset

 is the residual of an OLS regression of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\skillPrice_{s,\pYear}-\ln\skillPrice_{HSG,\pYear}$
\end_inset

 on a constant time trend.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Aggregate labor supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I need to construct aggregate labor supplies in efficiency units; see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LaborMarket"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The difficulty: not all cohorts that contribute to labor supply in the early
 / late data years have model counterparts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In constructing aggregate labor supplies, I assume that cohorts born before
 the earliest model cohort look like the average of the first 5 +++ model
 cohorts.
 Similarly, cohorts born after 
\begin_inset Formula $\bYearLast$
\end_inset

 look like the average of the last 5 +++ model cohorts.
 That is, they have the same 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tEndow$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 profiles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then I construct 
\begin_inset Formula $\lSupply_{s,\pYear}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LaborMarket"

\end_inset

 where the mass of persons in each cell 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{s,\bYear}$
\end_inset

 is taken directly from the data in the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{N}_{\age,s,\pYear}$
\end_inset

 (which is allowed to vary by age).
 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\age,s,\bYear}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{\age,s,\bYear}$
\end_inset

 are of course generated by the model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fixed parameters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wages are expressed in year 
\begin_inset Formula $\cpiBaseYear$
\end_inset

 prices.
 The gross interest rate is set to 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\grossInt$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:ParamFixed"

\end_inset

 summarizes these parameter values.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Fixed parameters
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "tab:ParamFixed"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset CommandInset include
LatexCommand include
filename "so1/set006/out/param_fixed_tb.tex"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Calibrated Parameters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Params"

\end_inset

 shows the values of the calibrated parameters.
 The curvature of the human capital production function is unusually low.
 Common estimates place 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 near 0.8 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BrowningHb1999"

\end_inset

.
 The calibrated values are between 
\begin_inset Formula $\alphaLow$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alphaHigh$
\end_inset

.
 This may reflect a difference in the way 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is estimated here.
 Earlier work, such as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Heckman1976"

\end_inset

 treats the cross-sectional age profile of earnings as representing the
 longitudinal profile for a hypothetical cohort.
 The resulting earnings profile is strongly hump-shaped (see Figure 13 in
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "Heckman1976"

\end_inset

), which contrasts with the longitudinal profiles observed in CPS data.
 More recent work, such as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HeckmanLochnerT1998"

\end_inset

, uses longitudinal data for a single cohort; in this case the cohort born
 in 1960 and observed until age 35.
 My estimate uses longitudinal wage profiles for several cohorts, most of
 which are observed until age 
\begin_inset Formula $\wageAgeRangeLast$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The depreciation rate of human capital range from 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddhLow$
\end_inset

% to 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddhHigh$
\end_inset

%.
 These are higher than common estimates found in the literature.
 Notably, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HeckmanLochnerT1998"

\end_inset

 set 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=0$
\end_inset

 based on the observation that age-wage profiles seem roughly flat at older
 ages when theory suggests that training investment should be zero.
 Due to the lower value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, training investment remains positive until the agent approaches retirement
 (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:ResultHInvest"

\end_inset

).
 Accounting for roughly flat wages then requires positive depreciation.
\end_layout

