\begin_layout Section
Results
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Results"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Accounting for Cohort Wage Profiles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Show that model does a good job replicating age wage profiles for all cohorts
 and school groups.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Measure fit by 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}=1-RSS/TSS$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $RSS$
\end_inset

 is the weighted sum of squared model residuals (model log median wage -
 data log median wage) and 
\begin_inset Formula $TSS$
\end_inset

 is the weighted total sum of squared residuals in the data.
 Weights are square root of number of observations in each (age, school,
 cohort) cell.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall fit is 0.95 +++
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Std dev of residuals = 0.05
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By school group 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 ranges from 0.84+++ for HSG to 0.92+++ for CG (cal_fit_so1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
std dev of residuals ranges from 0.05+++ for CG to 0.08 for HSG.
 [make a table]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
could ask: how good is that fit relative to stat models: fixed exper effects;
 no cohort effects +++
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Visual assessment of fit is provided in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Model-Fit-HSG"

\end_inset

, which compares the model generated age wage profiles with their data counterpa
rts for HSG.
 9 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\nCohorts$
\end_inset

 model cohorts.
 The same for CG in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Model-Fit-CG"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
plots for other groups in Appendix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Key data feature for both groups: shape of wage profiles changes over time.
 Model replicates these changes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is apparent that some of the profiles are not consistent with human capital
 theory and constant skill prices.
 The age profiles for those not college educated are essentially flat.
 Those for college graduates are not concave.
 Note also that the longitudinal wage profiles look very different from
 cross-sectional profiles that are sometimes used in their stead.
 They also look very different from the age wage profiles that sometimes
 estimated using panel data and imposing that a fixed age profile, combined
 with either year effects or cohort effects, characterizes all cohorts (e.g.,
 Figure 3 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "Huggett2006"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

