\begin_layout Standard
To see changes in shapes more clearly, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:InterceptsSlopes"

\end_inset

 show intercepts and slopes of cohort specific profiles.
 For all school groups, slopes have a U shape with min near 1950 birth cohort.
 Intercepts decline over most of the period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intercepts and slopes are inversely related.
 During the expansion of U.S.
 education up to the cohorts born in the early 1950s, all wage profiles
 became flatter over time, while their intercepts increased.
 After the early 1950s birth cohorts, U.S.
 education growth essentially stopped.
 During this period, wage profiles became steeper with lower intercepts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Model replicates without cohort effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Explain later how this works.
 Roughly: cohorts born in periods of fast skill price growth invest a lot
 in human capital.
 Their wage profiles have low intercepts and high slopes.
\end_layout

